{{Korean name|Kim}} {{Infobox football biography | name = Kim Jong-hun | image = | caption = | birth_date = {{Birth date and age|1956|09|01}} | birth_place = [[Pyongyang]], [[North Korea]] | death_date = | height = | position = [[Defender (association football)|Defender]] | currentclub = [[Sobaeksu Sports Club|Sobaeksu]] | youthyears1 = | youthclubs1 = | years1 = | clubs1 = [[April 25 Sports Club]] | caps1 = | goals1 = | totalcaps = | totalgoals = | nationalyears1 = 1973–1985 | nationalteam1 = [[Korea DPR national football team|Korea DPR]] | nationalcaps1 = 4 | nationalgoals1 = 0 | medaltemplates = | manageryears1 = ????–2007 | managerclubs1 = [[April 25 Sports Club|April 25]] | manageryears2 = 2007–2010 | managerclubs2 = [[Korea DPR national football team|Korea DPR]] | manageryears3 = 2011- | managerclubs3 = [[Sobaeksu Sports Club|Sobaeksu]] | club-update = | nationalteam-update = }} {{Infobox Korean name | title = [[Korean name]] | hangul = {{linktext|김|정|훈}} | hanja = {{linktext|金|正|勳}} | rr = Gim Jeong-hun | mr = Kim Chŏng-hun }}
'''Kim Jong-hun''' (born September 1, 1956) is a retired North Korean [[Association football|football]] player and the former head coach of the [[North Korea national football team]]. He led the nation's team to and during the [[2010 FIFA World Cup]].
== Biography == As a player, Kim Jong-hun has spent his career at [[April 25 Sports Club]].<ref name=FIFAOfficialProfile>{{Citation|title=KIM Jong Hun |url=https://www.fifa.com/worldcup/teams/team=43821/coach.html |publisher=[[FIFA]] |accessdate=2010-06-18 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100615215613/http://www.fifa.com/worldcup/teams/team%3D43821/coach.html |archivedate=2010-06-15 |df= }}</ref> He was capped four times for North Korea during the qualifications for the [[1974 FIFA World Cup|1974]] and [[1986 FIFA World Cup]]s.<ref name=FIFAOfficialProfile />
After ending his player career, Kim became a manager. He managed April 25 Sports Team until 2007, when he became the manager of North Korea national team.<ref name=FIFAOfficialProfile /> In 2009, he led the team as it qualified for the [[2010 FIFA World Cup]], their first since [[1966 FIFA World Cup|1966]].<ref>{{Citation |title=After 43 years, North Korea back in Europe |url=http://www.cbssports.com/soccer/story/12323646 |publisher=[[CBS Sports]] |date=2009-10-07 |accessdate=2009-10-11}}</ref><ref>{{Citation |title=Kim ecstatic as North Korea make World Cup |url=http://soccernet.espn.go.com/news/story?id=655657&cc=5901 |publisher=[[ESPN]] |date=2009-06-18 |accessdate=2009-10-11}}</ref>
After a disappointing showing at the World Cup, Kim faced harsh criticism upon his return to North Korea. [[Radio Free Asia]] reported that he was publicly shamed and condemned for hours in front of 400 people, including the North Korean sports minister.<ref name="rfa">{{cite news | newspaper= Radio Free Asia | title= World Cup Team Shamed, Reprimanded | date=July 28, 2010 | url= http://www.rfa.org/english/news/korea/worldcup-07282010173446.html | author1= Moon Sung-hui | last2 = Jackson-Han | first2= Sarah }}</ref>
At the same event, the team members were commanded to individually criticize their coach, who was accused of betraying General [[Kim Jong-un]], the country's [[heir apparent]].<ref name="rfa"/> The report also mentioned that he had been stripped of his membership in the [[Workers' Party of Korea]] and forced to work hard labor on a construction site as punishment.<ref name="rfa"/> It is however unknown whether Kim was really faced with such a violating punishment, as far as DPRK has its information mostly closed from the other world. Little is known about Kim Jong-hun's current (by October 2018) occupation, probably due to the same reason.
