{{Infobox venue | name = Stade olympique de Sousse | nickname = '''Invaders Cemetery - مقبرة الغزاة''' | logo_image = | logo_caption = | image = Stade olympique de Sousse, 13 avril 2016.jpg | caption = | fullname = | former_names = | location = [[Sousse]], [[Tunisia]] | coordinates = {{Coord|35|49|24|N|10|36|46|E|type:landmark|display=inline,title}} | broke_ground = | built = | opened = 1973 | renovated = 1994 | expanded = 1999 | closed = | demolished = | owner = [[Government of Tunisia]] | operator = | surface = Grass | scoreboard = | estimated_cost = | suites = | architect = | project_manager = | structural engineer = | services engineer = | general_contractor = | main_contractors = | capacity = 28,000<ref>http://stadiumdb.com/stadiums/tun/stade_olympique_de_sousse</ref> | record_attendance = 30,000 | executive_suites = | dimensions = 105 m × 65 m | acreage = | tenants =[[Étoile du Sahel]] }}
The '''Stade olympique de Sousse''' ({{Lang-ar|الملعب الأولمبي بسوسة}}) is a [[multi-purpose stadium]] in [[Sousse]], [[Tunisia]]. It is used by the [[football (soccer)|football]] team [[Étoile du Sahel]], and was used for the [[2004 African Cup of Nations]]. The stadium holds 28,000 people. It hosts within it the meetings played by the football team of the city: Étoile sportive du Sahel (ESS).
For many decades, [[Sousse]] footballers knew only the clay surfaces and knew the turf surfaces only when the stadium was inaugurated with an initial capacity of 10,000 places. It passes over the years to 15,000 seats and is then expanded again on the occasion of the [[1994 African Cup of Nations]] with 6,000 additional seats to reach a capacity of 21,000 seats; A luminous panel is installed at the same time. The last expansion was carried out in 1999 to bring the capacity of the stadium to 28,000 seats for the [[2001 Mediterranean Games]], a reorganization of the gallery of honor was carried out, from a capacity of 70 to 217 places. The stadium has yet to be expanded to reach the capacity of 49,000 seats after the announcement the president of the club [[:fr:Moez Driss|Moez Driss]] in May 2008.
It hosted [[1977 FIFA World Youth Championship]], [[1994 African Cup of Nations]], [[2001 Mediterranean Games]] and [[2004 African Cup of Nations]].
