{{Infobox venue | name = Värendsvallen | nickname = | native_name = | native_name_lang = | fullname = | former names = | logo_image = | logo_caption = | image = 120603 Värendsvallen 4600.jpg | image_size = 200px | image_alt = | caption = Värendsvallen | pushpin_map = | pushpin_mapsize = | pushpin_map_caption = | pushpin_label_position = | address = | location = [[Växjö]], [[Sweden]] | coordinates = | type = [[sports ground]] | genre = | broke_ground = | built = | opened = {{Start date|df=y|1966}} | renovated = | expanded = | closed = | demolished = | owner = | operator = | surface = | scoreboard = | cost = | architect = | project_manager = | structural engineer = | services engineer = | general_contractor = | main_contractors = | seating_type = | capacity = | suites = | record_attendance = | dimensions = | field_shape = | acreage = | volume = | tenants = [[Östers IF]] (1966–2012) | embedded = | website = | publictransit = }} {{Unreferenced|date=December 2009}} '''Värendsvallen''' is a [[multi-purpose stadium]] in [[Växjö]], [[Sweden]]. It is currently used mostly for [[football (soccer)|football]] matches and was the home stadium of [[Östers IF]] until September 2012. The stadium currently holds 15,062 people and was built in 1966. The highest attendance ever was 26,404 against IK Brage in 1967, in the qualifying game for Allsvenskan. The following season, Öster averaged an attendance of 15,622 on their road to the club's [[1968 Allsvenskan|first Swedish Championship]]. On March 31, 2011 work started on [[Myresjöhus Arena]], the stadium was opened in September 2012 and replaced Värendsvallen as Östers home ground. Värendsvallen will be transformed into an athletics arena.
